## Step 1: Examine Reads

**Read length distribution**

``` bash
# Unzips the raw data and sends the data to standard output
zcat raw_data/raw_reads.fastq.gz \
# This is a pipe. It sends output from the previous command as input to the next command
  | \
# Here we select only the top 40k lines in the file. This equates to 10k reads. It should be plenty to get some stats
  head -n 40000 | \
# This is a small bioawk program. It prints the name of each sequence followed by its length
  bioawk -c fastx '{print $name,length($seq)}' \
# Send outputs to a file called read_lengths.txt
  > read_lengths.txt
```

```{r}
library(tidyverse)

rl_data <- read_tsv("../read_lengths.txt",col_names = c("id","length"), show_col_types = FALSE)

ggplot(rl_data, aes(x=length/1000)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 2) +
  xlab("Read Length Kb") + ylab("Number of Reads")
```

**Figure 1.** Histogram of reads lengths in the mock nanopore sequencing dataset.

**Calculating read N50**

```{r}
total_len <- sum(rl_data$length)

rl_data %>% 
  arrange(desc(length)) %>%  # longest reads first
  mutate(cumsum = cumsum(length)) %>%  # running total of bases
  filter(cumsum>total_len/2) %>%  # keep rows after halfway point (N50)
  head(n=1) # first row is the N50 read
```

So we expect that the N50 of our assembly should be \> 22Kb.

# Step 2: Assembly

**Question 3.1** The largest contig has 4,681,059 bp and a depth of 21.0 x. Depth = coverage depth.

**Question 3.2** Based on depth, and the fact it has only 1 chromosome (no links/nodes), it is *Geitlerinema sp. PCC 7407*.

**Question 3.3** Locate two circular chromosomes for Vibrio alfacsensis in bandage. Use the outputs from gc.awk to help with this. I am not sure but I am leaning towards edge_40;edge_9 since they both have the correct depth coverage and the sum of their size roughly corresponds to the expected size.

# Step 3: Basic Assembly QC

```{r}
gc <- read_tsv("../assembly_check/assembly.gc.tsv",col_names = c("#seq_name","length","GC"))
info <- read_tsv("../flye/mock/assembly_info.txt") 

# Joining both datasets
gc_info <- info %>% 
  left_join(gc)

gc_info %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=GC)) + geom_histogram() + ylab("Number of contigs")
```

**Figure 2.** Histogram of GC content values for assembled contigs in a flye assembly of the mock community dataset.

```{r}
# Data wrangling
gc_info %>% 
  filter(GC<0.8) %>% 
  filter(cov.<25) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=GC,y=cov.)) + geom_point(aes(size=length)) + ylab("Coverage depth")
```

**Figure 3.** Coverage and GC content of assembled contigs in the mock community assembly. Contigs lengths are shown through point size.

**Question 3.4** The cluster of contigs with high GC content (\>60%) and coverage depth around 7.5x is likely to be *Desulfovibrio sulfodismutans*.

```{r}
# Adding labels
#install.packages("ggrepel")
library(ggrepel)
gc_info %>% 
  filter(GC<0.8) %>% 
  filter(cov.<25) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=GC,y=cov.)) + geom_point(aes(size=length)) + geom_label_repel(aes(label=`#seq_name`))
```

**Figure 4.** Coverage and GC content of assembled contigs in the mock community assembly. Contigs lengths are shown through point size. Only contigs with more than 25x coverage and less than 80% GC coverage are shown.

**Question 3.5**

```{r}
# Sum reference lengths
sum_length <- sum(gc$length)
sum_length_gc_info <- sum(gc_info$length)

# Assembly length
assembly_length <- (sum_length/total_len)*100
```

The total length is 18,315,582 bp and the proportion is 12.3. \*\* I think my assemblage is slightly different. I noticed that my graph are not exactly the same as those in the workbook, so it makes sense that my sizes are slgihtly different as well.

# Step 4: Binning

Grouping contigs based on nucleotide composition and read coverage using metabat2 on Terminal.

``` bash
# Prepare an input file summarising read depth information for all contigs

cat ../flye/mock/assembly_info.txt  | grep -v '#' | awk '{OFS="\t";print $1,$3}' > depths.txt

# Creating a compatible file with same order as previous 
cat depths.txt | awk '{print $1}' | xargs samtools faidx ../flye/mock/assembly.fasta > assembly_ordered.fasta

# Run metabat
metabat2 -i assembly_ordered.fasta -a depths.txt --cvExt -o bins/metabat --seed 5
```

# Step 5:

Checking bin quality with checkM. Created a new directory, sourced bins and added our longest contig (edge_28). Submitted shell through:

``` bash
sbatch run_checkm.sh
```
**Question 3.6** I think Bin 3 (root) and Bin 4 (Deltaproteobacteria) could potentially be contaminated since they are the only ones not returning as Vibrio.

















